Thanks for watching this video. I'm glad you're here. If you feel like this earns your subscription please click here: http://bit.ly/Subscribe2SED


How this happened: I messaged Tory "If you ever find yourself with an open lunch I'll buy. No cameras, just rocket geek chat."
A few months later he changed a flight one day so we could grab lunch, but he also carved out a couple of hours before lunch to give me a personal tour.
He's as cool off camera as he is on camera. He allowed me to ask any technical question I had, and I never even got close to the limits of his understanding of rockets. His technical prowess is something I aspire to. We made a video on the second channel where I interview him about more specific things about rockets, as well as how he feels about competitors.
2nd Channel Interview with Tory about rocket engines, competitors, and business philosophy: https://youtu.be/DQaPOIQLEUo

snippet.textDisplay: I absolutely LOVED this video.  I've always wondered what the manufacturing process behind these incredible machines is like, and it DID NOT DISAPPOINT!  As someone who has spent a comparably tiny amount of time around machining tools, it  fascinates me that these craftspeople are using tools and techniques that I've learned but with such incredible quantities, and precision.  I've done milling, forming, etching, and welding, but only ever on jewelry, and it's so incredible to see these same techniques that have existed for thousands of years are not only still alive today, but also critical to our exploration of space.  Humans are absolutely incredible, and it's so inspiring to see how just increasing tolerances and precision can get you from making a tankard to making a rocket.  Same techniques, but orders of magnitude different in scale and precision.  So cool!  Thank for this video, Destin, and thanks to Tory for allowing you to share it with us!

snippet.textDisplay: First lets explain who ULA actually is: Founders: Lockheed Martin · Boeing, 2 major US Government contracted military contractors.  Oh, did I leave out the word "bloated"?  These company's have in the past build incredible tech products, but at a hugely inflated cost to the American Taxpayer.  Now that they are having to compete with independent commercial contractors, the corners they are cutting to meet budgets are causing failures. One reason they were NOT selected for the first American Crewed Launch to the ISS.  If it weren't for an institutional history of political kickbacks, lobbing and corruption, Boeing and Lockheed could be doing much better work. I hope they find their way and do so.  Their expertise is needed.
